{{Orphan|date=October 2016}}
{{Infobox football biography | name = Sead Gorani | image = | fullname = Sead Gorani | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1977|1|17}} | birth_place = [[Prizren]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]] | height = {{Height|m=}} | position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]] | currentclub = | clubnumber = | youthyears1 = 1986–1994 | youthclubs1 = [[KF Liria|Liria]] | years1 = 1994–1995 | years2 = 1995–1998 | years3 = 1998–2001 | years4 = | years5 = 2003–2004 | years6 = 2005–2008 | clubs1 = [[Zeytinburnuspor]] | clubs2 = [[FK Ibar|Ibar Rožaje]] | clubs3 = [[FK Železnik|Železnik]] | clubs4 = [[PFC Naftex Burgas|Naftex Burgas]] | clubs5 = [[FK Pobeda|Pobeda Prilep]] | clubs6 = [[KF Liria|Liria]] | caps1 = | caps2 = | caps3 = <ref>Note: Missing stats for the 1998/99 season.</ref> 5 | caps4 = | caps5 = | caps6 = | goals1 = | goals2 = | goals3 = 0 | goals4 = | goals5 = | goals6 = | nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = | manageryears1 = 2006– | managerclubs1 = Winner Prizren (youth) }} '''Sead Gorani''' (born 17 January 1977) is a [[Kosovo|Kosovar]] [[Association football|football]]er who played in clubs from FR Yugoslavia, Turkey, Bulgaria, Macedonia and Kosovo. After retiring, he became in charge, along his father, of a football school Winner in his hometown Prizren.
==Career== Born in [[Prizren]],<ref name="winner">[http://www.info-ks.net/clanak.php?id=12328&naziv=skola&nav_id=2&pod_nav=2 Rasadnik mladih talenata] at info-ks.net, 22-1-2011, retrieved 17-10-2016 {{sr icon}}</ref> [[Socialist Autonomous Province of Kosovo]], [[SR Serbia]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]] (modern [[Kosovo]]), Gorani started playing in local club [[KF Liria]] at age of 9, and he spent his entire youth career there.<ref name="winner"/> He then moved abroad and played one season as left-winger with [[Zeytinburnuspor]], playing at time in the Turkish [[Süper Lig]].<ref name="winner"/> At age of 18 he, returned to FR Yugoslavia, and signed with Montenegrin side [[FK Ibar|FK Ibar Rožaje]] playing back then in the [[Second League of FR Yugoslavia]].<ref name="winner"/>
In summer 1998, coming from FK Ibar, he moved to Serbian and Yugoslav capital [[Belgrade]] and joined [[FK Železnik]].<ref>[http://fcobilic.tripod.com/yu1liga.html 1998/99 First League of FR Yugoslavia clubs presentation] at fcobilic.tripod.com</ref> He played with Železnik in the [[1999–2000 First League of FR Yugoslavia]] making four appearances<ref>"Fudbalski godišnjak 1999/2000", page 20 {{sr icon}}</ref> and in the [[2000–01 First League of FR Yugoslavia]] making one appearance.<ref>"Godišnjak Fudbalskog saveza Jugoslavije 2000/2001", page 20 {{sr icon}}</ref>
After a spell with Bulgarian side [[PFC Naftex Burgas]],<ref name="winner"/> he played with [[FK Pobeda]] in the [[2003–04 Macedonian First Football League]]<ref>[http://en.eufo.de/index/squad/pobeda-prilep/2003-04 Pobeda Prilep 2003/04 squad] at EUFO.de</ref> becoming Macedonian champion, and later, with Kosovar side [[KF Liria]] in the season 2005–06.<ref>[http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/sead-gorani/ Sead Gorani] at Worldfootball.net</ref>
Sead Gorani is son of former football player and coach Šukrija Gorani, and along his father, Sead has been in charge of football school Winner in Prizren since 2006. By 2011, Sead had been retired from his playing career three years earlier as result of a cirgury he had to be submitted to, and has been coaching the youth teams at Winner five years already.<ref name="winner"/> On 21 June 2013, representatives of KF Liria and three local football schools, one of them being Sead Gorani representing Winner, met with representatives of the Commission for Culture, Youth and Sports in order to improve the investments in football in the city of Prizren.<ref>[http://prizrenpress.com/sport/sporti-ne-prizren-mjerueshem/ Sporti në Prizren, i mjerueshëm] at PrizrenPress.com, 21-6-2013, retrieved 17-10-2016 {{sq icon}}</ref>
